<subSubSection pageId="92" pageNumber="93" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="92.[700,1229,193,1155]" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">
ETYMOLOGY: The specific epithet 
<taxonomicName authorityName="OPITZ" authorityYear="2005" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Aphelocerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="92" pageNumber="93" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="propinquus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">propinquus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(near) is a Latin name that I use here to indicate the close relationship between the members of this species and those of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Chevrolat)" baseAuthorityName="Chevrolat" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Clerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="92" pageNumber="93" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scutellaris">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">A. scutellaris</emphasis>
(Chevrolat)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
